Three agents — a floor associate next to the stopped robot, a robotics engineer at the operations desk, and a fleet safety coordinator at the safety console — coordinate over a shared radio channel to recover stopped warehouse robots across {{ round_count }} rounds. Every character sent on the radio costs one simulated second (fixed per-round budget: {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}s). If total communication time exceeds the budget, the round fails and the robot stays stopped.

The same visible symptoms can mean different things depending on the robot's diagnostic profile and live fleet state, so the floor associate cannot solve a round alone. The engineer holds a live recovery sheet that rotates per robot model, firmware state, and fleet mode — they cannot solve alone either, because they cannot see warehouse traffic. The safety coordinator sees the live aisle locks, worker zones, and which physical actions are currently allowed — but cannot diagnose the robot fault. Every round, all three perspectives must combine before the floor associate calls perform_recovery.

Twelve named robot faults are combined into per-round cases ({{ fault_count_min }}–{{ fault_count_max }} faults per robot, drawn from the catalog by a deterministic seed). Recovery procedures are rendered each round with rotating wait-times, intensities, and surfaces so even agents that memorize the fault names cannot bypass asking the engineer for the current procedure.

Round success requires all of: the action targets the correct robot, addresses every live fault, follows the engineer's required step order, uses the engineer's required wait times, respects every safety-coordinator restriction, performs no forbidden action, stays within the communication budget, and leaves the robot in a safe operating state. The LLM judge scores the seven non-budget criteria per round; the communication budget is checked deterministically.
